Implement a comprehensive error handling system for GraphQL that supports partial responses. You need to:

- Handle field-level errors without failing entire query
- Collect multiple errors and return them in a structured format
- Implement error path tracking to identify which fields failed
- Support custom error codes and error details
- Implement error formatting middleware
- Handle both synchronous and asynchronous field resolution errors
- Preserve successfully resolved fields while reporting failures

**Function signature:**
typescript
interface ErrorDetail {
  message: string;
  code: string;
  path: (string | number)[];
  details?: Record<string, unknown>;
}

interface PartialResponse<T> {
  data: Partial<T> | null;
  errors: ErrorDetail[];
}

class GraphQLErrorHandler {
  executeQuery<T>(query: string, variables?: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<PartialResponse<T>>;
  formatError(error: unknown, path: (string | number)[]): ErrorDetail;
}


**Example:**
Query requests user with posts:
graphql
query {
  user(id: "1") {
    name
    email
    posts {
      title
      content
    }
  }
}


If user resolution succeeds but posts resolution fails:

{
  "data": {
    "user": {
      "name": "John",
      "email": "john@example.com",
      "posts": null
    }
  },
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "Failed to fetch posts",
      "code": "POSTS_LOAD_ERROR",
      "path": ["user", "posts"]
    }
  ]
}


**Edge cases:**
- Errors in list field items (which items fail)
- Nested object resolution failures
- Database connection timeouts
- Authorization errors on specific fields
- Circular dependency in error reporting

